WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.160
Hello, I'm a data scientist at Mango Solutions, and as you all know, we have quite a lot of

00:00:15.160 --> 00:00:19.200
packages on CRAN, over 12,000 at the moment.

00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:23.200
That is brilliant to have that choice, but occasionally also a little overwhelming, especially

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:28.400
for people who are new to R. So, when you try to find the right package for your task,

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:45.000
two questions are likely to come up, I want to do X, which package or packages can I use,

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.439
and if you find several, you end up with a question, which one do I pick?

00:00:49.439 --> 00:00:51.880
And I'm not here because I have the answers.

00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:56.599
I don't think there are ultimate answers to this, but I want to share a workflow I've

00:00:56.599 --> 00:01:01.759
seen several people do and some tools for along the way.

00:01:01.759 --> 00:01:06.639
So first, you obviously need to find packages with the right functionality, so I'll be talking

00:01:06.639 --> 00:01:11.440
about that a bit, and then you usually have a selection of packages that you try to narrow

00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:16.239
down by some high-level comparisons, and then you just have to get in and explore them in

00:01:16.239 --> 00:01:20.400
more depth before you can make your choice.

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:24.480
One way to keep up with all the things that are out there, I don't necessarily would advocate

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:28.279
for this to be the most efficient way to understand what's out there, but certainly

00:01:28.279 --> 00:01:34.559
a fun way are all the different R blogs out there, and both R Weekly and R bloggers are

00:01:34.559 --> 00:01:39.839
aggregator sites, and you can contribute your own blog to it by providing them with your

00:01:39.839 --> 00:01:42.120
RSS feed.

00:01:42.120 --> 00:01:47.519
If you'd rather have search functionality, Rseek might be your thing.

00:01:47.519 --> 00:01:51.440
That is a Google custom search which gives you results from R-related sites like the

00:01:51.440 --> 00:01:58.480
R project site itself, GitHub, R bloggers, Stack Overflow and friends, and these kind

00:01:58.480 --> 00:01:59.480
of sites.

00:01:59.480 --> 00:02:05.440
Cran-tastic is a community site for R packages where you can search, review, and tag Cran

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:10.520
packages, and on Cran itself are the task views.

00:02:10.520 --> 00:02:16.360
They are in that menu on the left-hand side, but I've met quite a few people who are not

00:02:16.360 --> 00:02:19.720
aware of them, so I thought I'd point that out.

00:02:19.720 --> 00:02:25.520
They provide you with information about which packages are available given a certain topic

00:02:25.520 --> 00:02:30.919
like Bayesian inference, or natural language processing, or high-performance computing,

00:02:30.919 --> 00:02:36.240
or web interfaces, or psychometrics, or whatever floats your boat.

00:02:36.240 --> 00:02:44.839
These are usually curated lists where they group packages according to sub-topics.

00:02:44.839 --> 00:02:49.199
Curated lists are hard to keep up to date, so, if you spot something that you think should

00:02:49.199 --> 00:02:54.440
be on there, or want to contribute in any other way, I think the best way is to email

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:56.639
the maintainer of the task view.

00:02:56.639 --> 00:03:00.039
That should always be on the top with a name and an email address where you can contact

00:03:00.039 --> 00:03:02.119
that person.

00:03:02.119 --> 00:03:08.000
Another site is Metacran which aggregates information from Cran and GitHub.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:14.279
It also has search functionality and sections like featured packages, and trending packages,

00:03:14.279 --> 00:03:17.000
most downloaded, most dependent upon.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:23.639
So I think these kind of measures try to capture package popularity.

00:03:23.639 --> 00:03:27.960
That may be useful to discover what's out there, but also when you try to narrow down

00:03:27.960 --> 00:03:33.479
your selection, however, Metacran doesn't give you direct functionality to look at these

00:03:33.479 --> 00:03:38.520
numbers for your custom selection of packages.

00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:43.839
But let's give that high-level comparison another thought anyway, so, what other aspects

00:03:43.839 --> 00:03:46.240
might you be paying attention to?

00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:47.240
Is it stable?

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:49.240
Is it actively maintained?

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:51.600
When was the last update?

00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:53.039
What's going on in the issue tracker?

00:03:53.039 --> 00:03:55.479
Is it dependent upon what about tests?

00:03:55.479 --> 00:03:57.880
Does it use continuous integration?

00:03:57.880 --> 00:03:58.880
What about the documentation?

00:03:58.880 --> 00:04:01.199
Does the package have a vignette?

00:04:01.199 --> 00:04:04.720
These are all things that we could try to capture in metrics.

00:04:04.720 --> 00:04:09.440
I think many of us will probably also pay attention to who wrote the package.

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:14.119
That doesn't make for a good metric, though, so metrics are a tool.

00:04:14.119 --> 00:04:16.399
Use it as it's appropriate.

00:04:16.399 --> 00:04:22.760
I'm aware of at least two packages out there that collect package metrics, so one is creatively

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:30.160
named package metrics, that's a project that I worked on with these lovely people, and

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:32.239
Colin also contributed some code.

00:04:32.239 --> 00:04:38.239
It gives you information about, like, from Cran and GitHub, for example, when was the

00:04:38.239 --> 00:04:43.440
last commit, the last issue closed, how many contributors are there?

00:04:43.440 --> 00:04:45.320
These kind of things.

00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:51.399
At Mango, we also have a product where we check our packages in depth, and as part of

00:04:51.399 --> 00:04:56.320
that, we also have a package to collect package metrics, and we've made it available on GitHub

00:04:56.320 --> 00:05:01.679
that gives you similar Cran and GitHub stats along with cyclomatic complexity and a few

00:05:01.679 --> 00:05:09.239
others, but these metrics are obviously not a substitute for actually an in-depth exploration

00:05:09.239 --> 00:05:10.239
of a package.

00:05:10.519 --> 00:05:15.519
So sort of maybe on two ends of a formality spectrum, you could go and try it out yourself,

00:05:15.519 --> 00:05:23.000
play with a vignette, that kind of thing, or, yes, one minute!

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:29.640
Or you can rely on a formal review process, for example, through academic journals, like

00:05:29.640 --> 00:05:35.279
the Journal for Statistical Software, or the R Journal, or there's also the R OpenSight

00:05:35.279 --> 00:05:41.839
software review, and part of that review process at R OpenSight is the good practice

00:05:41.839 --> 00:05:47.239
package which is also a Mango package that I've recently released to Cran which lets

00:05:47.239 --> 00:05:55.040
you run a set of 230 checks on good practices for building R packages on there just to give

00:05:55.040 --> 00:06:00.399
you a quicker sense of maybe how that package was written than if you would open up and

00:06:00.399 --> 00:06:02.600
read the source code yourself.

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:09.040
And with that, I have a bunch of links for all the stuff that I've talked about, and

00:06:09.040 --> 00:06:13.480
I just want to say, like, many ways lead to Rome in this case, and all of these are tools,

00:06:13.480 --> 00:06:16.839
and pick the ones that are right for you and your task.

00:06:16.839 --> 00:06:19.359
Thank you, Hannah.

00:06:19.359 --> 00:06:26.040
Next on the program is Mikkel.

